StringWithMarkup.String: The NORMAN Suspect List Exchange (NORMAN-SLE) is a central access point for NORMAN members (and others) to find suspect lists relevant for their environmental monitoring questions.

This Exchange documents all individual collections that (will) form a part of NORMAN SusDat, the merged NORMAN Substance Database (DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2664077). Each list/collection has a DOI in Zenodo.
S25 | OECDPFAS | List of PFAS from the OECD

nodes.description: List of PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances) from the OECD, provided by Zhanyun Wang. PFAS are a group of man-made chemicals that includes PFOA, PFOS, GenX, and many other chemicals. Details in the Zenodo dataset. Extensive registration and curation performed by CompTox Dashboard team (see CompTox files). Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2648775

StringWithMarkup.String: S36 | UBAPMT | Potential Persistent, Mobile and Toxic (PMT) substances

Updated version provided by Hans Peter Arp, details in this technical note (UBA Report 126/2019, https://www.umweltbundesamt.de/publikationen/reach-improvement-of-guidance-methods-for-the) and in an upcoming second revised version of that report to be released in 2022. StringWithMarkup.String: S46 | PFASNTREV19 | List of PFAS reported in Non-Target HRMS Studies from Liu et al 2019

nodes.description: List of PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances) compiled in the non-target high resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) PFAS review by Liu et al 2019, DOI:10.1016/j.trac.2019.02.021. MS-ready list prepared by Yanna Liu, Lisa D'Agostino, Emma Schymanski and Jon Martin. Note not all entries have structures. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2656744

StringWithMarkup.String: S58 | PSYCHOCANNAB | Synthetic Cannabinoids and Psychoactive Compounds

nodes.description: A list of synthetic cannabinoids and psychoactive compounds assembled from public resources, from CompTox Chemicals Dashboard. A psychoactive drug, psychopharmaceutical, or psychotropic is a chemical substance that changes brain function and results in alterations in perception, mood, consciousness, cognition, or behavior. Synthetic cannabinoids are a class of molecules that bind to cannabinoid receptors in the body (the same receptors to which THC and CBD attach, which are cannabinoids in cannabis plants). Synthetic cannabinoids are also designer drugs that are often sprayed onto plant matter. This combined list is assembled from Wikipedia, public databases, and scientific literature. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3247723

StringWithMarkup.String: S50 | CCSCOMPEND | The Unified Collision Cross Section (CCS) Compendium

nodes.description: The Unified Collision Cross Section (CCS) Compendium contains >3800 experimental collision cross section values (drift tube MS) for multiple adducts, provided by Jackie Picache and John McLean, Vanderbilt. Further details available here: https://lab.vanderbilt.edu/mclean-group/collision-cross-section-database/. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2658162

StringWithMarkup.String: S96 | ECIPFAS | Updatable List to add PFAS Structures to Public Resources from ECI (UniLu)

nodes.description: This dataset is for users to contribute PFAS from the literature or other documents to the NORMAN SLE, SusDat and PubChem. Note that the role of this list is to enable the addition of new PFAS into databases and is not intended to be a comprehensive PFAS listing. The start of this collection was all PFAS entries in the S74_REFTPS dataset, which includes also legacy PFAS. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.6389740

StringWithMarkup.String: S11 | SWISSPEST | Swiss Insecticides, Fungicides and TPs

nodes.description: A list of Swiss Insecticides, Fungicides and TPs, included as Table S1 from Moschet et al. 2013. DOI:10.1021/ac4021598. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2623740

StringWithMarkup.String: S23 | EIUBASURF | Surfactant Suspect List from EI and UBA

nodes.description: A compiled list of eco-labeled surfactants from Environmental Institute (EI, SK) and the German Federal Environmental Agency (UBA, DE) assigning chemical structures to UVCB chemicals based on names and prior knowledge. Provided by Nikiforos Alygizakis, EI. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2648764

StringWithMarkup.String: S65 | UATHTARGETSGC | University of Athens GC-HRMS Target List

nodes.description: A list of targets (reference standards) for gas chromatography-atmospheric pressure chemical ionisation-high resolution mass spectrometry (GC-APCI-HRMS) from the University of Athens. Provided by the research group of Prof. Nikolaos Thomaidis. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3753372

StringWithMarkup.String: S40 | ALGALTOX | Algal toxins list from CompTox

nodes.description: List of algal toxins (generated during blooms) from the CompTox Chemicals Dashboard. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2656710

StringWithMarkup.String: S79 | UACCSCEC | Collision Cross Section (CCS) Library from UAntwerp

nodes.description: A library containing the collision cross section (CCS) values of 311 adducts of 148 contaminants of emerging concern (CECs) and their metabolites measured with drift tube ion mobility high resolution mass spectrometry (in positive and negative ionization modes with N2 as drift gas) as described in Belova et al (2021) DOI:10.1021/acs.analchem.1c00142. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.4704648

StringWithMarkup.String: S32 | REACH2017 | 2017 List of REACH Chemicals

nodes.description: A 2017 list of REACH chemicals including InChIKeys and spectral information, provided by N. Alygizakis and J. Slobodnik, EI. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.2653020

StringWithMarkup.String: S63 | UBADWGW | Substances Detected in Drinking (DW) or Groundwater (GW)

nodes.description: A list of REACH registered substances (Lists 5-7) detected in drinking (DW) or groundwater (GW) that do not meet PMT criteria, from the German Environmental Agency (UBA). Derived from a research project by Norwegian Geotechnical Institute (NGI). This couples with S36 UBAPMT (Lists 1-4) in the updated version provided by Hans Peter Arp, details in the technical note UBA Report 126/2019. Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3637629

StringWithMarkup.String: S83 | CCL5 | Contaminant Candidate List CCL 5 (Draft)

nodes.description: The CCL 5 is a (currently draft) list of contaminants that are currently not subject to any proposed or promulgated US primary drinking water regulations, but are known or anticipated to occur in public water systems. StringWithMarkup.String: S77 | FCCDB | Food Contact Chemicals Database v5.0

nodes.description: The Food Contact Chemicals database (FCCdb, DOI:10.5281/zenodo.3240108) is a compilation of information on over 12,000 intentionally added food contact chemicals extracted from publicly available sources such as legislation or industry inventories for different types of food contact materials and selected sources of hazard information, as described by Groh et al. 2021 (see DOI:10.1016/j.envint.2020.106225). Structural information for ~6000 entries where clear mappings could be found was added by P. Chirsir into FCCdb Version 5, prior to hosting it on the NORMAN Suspect List Exchange (see Dataset DOI:10.5281/zenodo.4625495). Further detailed descriptions for each sub-category in the classification tree can be found in the ReadMe tab of the FCCdb spreadsheet file, or in the respective sub-category tooltips ('?' boxes).

StringWithMarkup.String: Genotoxicity Calls from EFSA OpenFoodTox database

nodes.description: Provides results of genotoxicity studies recorded for this substances in the European Food Safety Authority's (EFSA) OpenFoodTox database.

Indicates if this substance is included on the European Chemicals Agency's (ECHA) list of plastic additives. The entry also shows the "main functions" as assigned by ECHA. The ECHA has performed and published in February 2019 a "Mapping exercise - Plastics additives initiative" (accessed at https://echa.europa.eu/de/mapping-exercise-plastic-additives-initiative in May 2019). This was "the joint project by ECHA and industry [which] resulted in a list of over 400 functional additives or pigments used in plastics, including information on the polymers they are most commonly found in and the typical concentration ranges." Further, "the mapping considered substances registered under REACH at above 100 tonnes per year, and focused on plasticizers, flame retardants, pigments, antioxidants, antistatic agents, nucleating agents and various types of stabilizers."

Indicates if this substance has been registered under REACH in the EU + shows the total tonnage registered in EU. Data were extracted from the ECHA's list downloaded in April 2019 from https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/registered-substances/

Indicates if the substance has been assessed and identified or not as a substance which could be problematic because of their persistence and mobility properties: PMT, persistent, mobile, toxic substances, or vPvM, very persistent very mobile substances, as listed in the 2019 report (126/2019) by the German Umweltbundesamt (UBA; German Environment Agency) Project No. (FKZ) 3716 67 416 0, Report No. FB000142/ENG, published in November 2019.  Title: REACH: Improvement of guidance and methods for the identification and assessmetn of PMT/vPvM substances. By Hans Peter H. Arp and Sarah E. Hale. Assessment quality, self-assigned by the authors, is also given (LQ, low quality; MQ, medium quality; HQ, high quality). ATTENTION: substances looked at by UBA were those registered in REACH by 2017; hence the assessment did not include substances registered only after this date.

StringWithMarkup.String: Included on EU Endocrine Disruptor Lists

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is included on one of the three Endocrine Disruptor Lists maintained by the Danish Environmental Protection Agency (see http://edlists.org), representing Denmark, and with participation of the respective national authorities of Belgium, the Netherlands, France, and Sweden. The three lists are: (I) Substances identified as endocrine disruptors at EU level, (II) Substances under evaluation for endocrine disruption under an EU legislation, (III) Substances considered, by the evaluating National Authority, to have endocrine disrupting properties. The names of responsible Member State authorities are: the Belgian Federal Public Service, Health, Food chain safety and environment; the Danish Environmental Protection Agency; Netherlands: The Ministry of Infrastructure and Water Management; French Agency for Food, Environmental and Occupational Health & Safety; Swedish Chemicals Agency (KEMI).

Indicates if this substance is included in the Chemicals in Plastic Packaging database (CPPdb), which compiled chemicals likely or possibly associated with plastic packaging. The entry also shows if the substance is included on the list A (chemicals likely associated with plastic packaging) or the list B (chemicals possibly assocaited with plastic packaging) of the CPPdb, and further indicates if it is considered to be allowed in food contact based on the records included in the CPPdb. The CPPdb was compiled as described in Groh et al. 2018 "Overview of known plastic packaging-associated chemicals and their hazards." Science of the Total Environment 651(2): 3253-3268. DOI 10.1016/j.scitotenv.2018.10.015

Indicates if the substance is listed on the European Chemiacls Agency's (ECHA) "PBT [persistence, bioaccumulation and toxicity] assessment list," downloaded on 30.04.2020 from http://echa.europa.eu/pbt . This list "includes the substances undergoing a PBT/vPvB assessment under REACH or the Biocidal Products Regulation that have been brought for discussion to ECHA's PBT Expert Group." The downloaded version has been last updated on 28.04.2020 and contained "176 unique substances/entries." The entry also shows the Status of the assessment, Outcome of the assessment, pursued Follow-up if any, date (year) of Assessment completion (if completed), and Authority (Member State) that has carried out the assessment; all data as provided in the ECHA's list.

StringWithMarkup.String: EDC recognized in the EU under REACH or Biocides regulation

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is recognized as an endocrine disrupting chemical in the EU under the REACH legislation (inclusion on the SVHC list due to endocrine disrupting properties with relevance for human health and/or the environment) or under the Biocides legislation (the latter according to the information in the List I of the EU Endocrine Disruptor Lists compiled by the Danish EPA (see http://edlists.org).

Indicates if the substance was included in the 2018 report by the UN Environmental Programme (UNEP; commissioned to International Panel on Chemical Pollution (IPCP)) as EDCs or potential EDCs identified by multiple robust stakeholders or by at least one robust stakeholder after a thorough scientific assessment performed based on the 2002 definition of an EDC or a potential EDC given by UNEP/International Program on Chemical Safety (IPCS). "multi-stakeholder involvement; identification publicly-accessible, thorough scientific assessment" are substances listed in Table 5 of the report. The substances identified like this all correspond to those classified as an EDC within the EU REACH (on SVHC list because of endocrine disruption-related concerns). There is, however, one substance (bisphenol A, CAS 80-05-7), which is classified as EDC by EU REACH but not listed in the UNEP  2018 report. The reason for this is that the report was drafted in July 2017, which was before the BPA was classified as EDC within the EU REACH. "at least one stakeholder; identification following a thorough scientific assessment" means the substance was identified as EDC or potential EDC after a thorough scientific assessment according to the 2002 WHO/IPCS definition performed by at least one 'robust' stakeholder, meaning either by the NGO International Chemical Secretariat (ChemSec) for inclusion on their SIN list, or by the Danish Centre on Endocrine Disruptors. The reference for the UNEP 2018 report on EDCs: UNEP (2018). "Overview Report I: Worldwide initiatives to identify endocrine disrupting chemicals (EDCs) and potential EDCs. July 2017." Prepared by: The International Panel on Chemical Pollution (IPCP). See also https://www.unenvironment.org/explore-topics/chemicals-waste/what-we-do/emerging-issues/scientific-knowledge-endocrine-disrupting/ (UN environment's webpage "Scientific knowledge of endocrine disrupting chemicals.")

StringWithMarkup.String: Danish EPA's predicted GHS-aligned classifications for HH or ENVH

nodes.description: This column shows if the substance has been assessed by the Danish Environmental Protection Agency (Danish EPA) with in silico / (Q)SAR methods that this agency used to predict GHS-aligned health hazard (HH) and environmental hazard (ENVH) classifications in order to provide an advisory resources for companies assessing  their substances under the EU Classification, Labeling and Packaging legislation, with a database for over 50'000 substances released in 2018. The column also shows the advisory (i.e., predicted) HH and ENVH classifications assigned to the substance in this assessmetn by the Danish EPA. Data was downloaded from https://clp-vejlliste.mst.dk/default.aspx on July 15, 2019.

StringWithMarkup.String: On EU REACH Authorization List, Annex XIV

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the Authorization list (Annex XIV) within REACH regulation (https://echa.europa.eu/authorisation-list ), Status April 2020. The entry also provides Reasons for inclusion, as listed in the Authorization list. See also https://www.echa.europa.eu/web/guest/regulations/reach/understanding-reach/

Indicates if the substance is listed on the SIN list (http://chemsec.org/business-tool/sin-list/ ). The entry also provides the reasons for inclusion as given by SIN list developers. The downloaded version of the SIN list was last updated in November 2019.

Indicates if the substance is a potential endocrine disruptors included on the TEDX list. Downloaded on 30.04.2019 from https://endocrinedisruption.org/interactive-tools/tedx-list-of-potential-endocrine-disruptors/ . The TEDX list was last updated in September 2018. The TEDX stands for The Endocrine Disruption Exchange. This organization, founded in 2003 by Dr. Theo Colborn, was closed on November 30, 2019, due to lack of funding.
Indicates (in case the substance is listed on the SIN list), to which "Use groups" has it been assigned by SIN list creators within the latest release in November 2019.

StringWithMarkup.String: Substances of genotoxic concern, prioritized by van Bossuyt et al. 2017, 2018

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance has been identified as a priority substance that requires further investigation because of genotoxicity concern. Identifies 106 substances predicted positive in 4 (Q)SAR tools for mutagenicity by van Bossuyt et al. 2017 (Van Bossuyt M. et al., 2017. (Q)SAR tools for priotity setting: A case study with printed paper and board food contact material substances. Food and Chemical Toxicology. 102: 109-119. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.fct.2017.02.002 ); 19 substances among these were identified as "very high priority for investgation of actual use and migration" by van Bossuyt et al. 2018 (van Bossuyt M. et al., 2018. Prioritizing substances of genotoxic concern for in-depth safety evaluation using non-animal approaches: The example of food contact materials. ALTEX 36: 215-230. https://doi.org/10.14573/altex.1810011).

Includes the following classifications related to substances which could be problematic because of their persistence properties: (a) PBT/vPvB status of the substances in the EU, i.e., on REACH Candidate list, see https://echa.europa.eu/candidate-list-table and from PBT/vPvB assessments carried out under the previous EU chemicals legislation, see https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/pbt-vpvb-assessments-under-the-previous-eu-chemicals-legislation. (b) Listed as PBT on U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA) list of persistent, bioaccumulative, and toxic (PBT) substances, see http://www.scorecard.goodguide.com/chemical-groups/one-list.tcl?short_list_name=pbt (c) Substance's inclusion on the list of restricted or banned POPs (persistent organic pollutants) as ruled by the Stockholm convention, see http://chm.pops.int/TheConvention/ThePOPs/ListingofPOPs/tabid/2509/Default.aspx (d) status and outcomes of PBT/vPvB assessments carried out by the EU before REACH legislation came into force in 2006 (i.e., "early assessments"). (e) PBT and/or vPvB status given by the concluded assessment by the Member State, as indicated in the ECHA's PBT assessment list (see next column).

Indicates if the substances can be found in the Toxicity Values (ToxVal) database compiled by the US Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) and available through its Computational Toxicology (CompTox) chemistry dashboard. The consulted version was version 5 (release of August 2018), downloaded from http://comptox.epa.gov/dashboard/chemical_lists/TOXVAL_V5. According to the US EPA's description, "as of August 2018 the ToxVal Database contains the following data: 772,721 toxicity values from 29 sources of data, 21,507 sub-sources, 4585 journals cited and 69,833 literature citations. Number of chemicals: 56,314." A publication by Williams et al. 2017 in the Journal of Chemoinformatics 9:61, doi 10.1186/s13321-017-0247-6, explains that in addition to toxicity data obtained from published literature, the ToxVal database also stores a wide range of structured toxicity data collected from international sources including US EPA, Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), European Chemicals Agency (ECHA), US National Library of Medicine (NLM), Hazardous Substances Data Bank (HSDB), and the European Union's (EU) Joint Research Centre (JRC). The numbers following the "yes" indicating that the substance is found in the ToxVal database give the number of recorded data sub-sources; number of PubMed articles; number of PubChem data sources; and count in the CPDat (The Chemicals and Products Database, for further details see description to the FCCdb source S01 above).

Indicates if the substance potentially could be classified as having the highest hazard grade for aquatic chronic toxicity (i.e., Aquatic Chronic 1), with or without Aquatic Acute 1 classification, based on the Danish EPA's predicted GHS-aligned hazard classifications.

StringWithMarkup.String: In EFSA's Open Food Tox database

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed in the European Food Safety Authority's (EFSA) OpenFoodTox database. This database provides chemical hazards data for substances that have ever been evaluated by EFSA since its creation in 2002, as extracted by the EFSA staff from "risk assessments for almost 5000 unique substances in over 2040 Scientific Opinions, Statements and Conclusions through the work of its scientific Panels, Units and Scientific Committee." The consulted version of the OpenFoodTox database was downloaded in April 2020 from https://zenodo.org/record/3693783#.Xq1dY2gzZaQ . This is the Version 3 of this database, which was published on March 27, 2020 and has the DOI 10.5281/zenodo.3693783. Consolidated DOI always resolving to the newest version is 10.5281/zenodo.780543.

StringWithMarkup.String: On New Zealand list of chemicals (NZIOC)

nodes.description: Indicates if this substance is listed on the New Zealand Inventory of Chemicals (NZIoC) list. The list was accessed in May 2019 at http://www.cirs-reach.com/Inventory/New_Zealand_Inventory_of_Chemicals_NZIoC.html. This is "a database of all the hazardous chemical components of products approved under group standards. Many group standards require the hazardous components of products covered under these approvals to be listed on the NZIoC."

StringWithMarkup.String: On EU REACH SVHC List (Candidate list for authorization)

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the Candidate list of SVHC (substances of very high concern) for Authorization, maintained under REACH regulation (https://echa.europa.eu/candidate-list-table). The entry also lists the Art. 57-relevant properties (Art. 57 a-f outlines substance's properties that would justify its inclusion on the Candidate list of SVHCs) as provided in the ECHA's list. Status April 2020. See also REACH: https://www.echa.europa.eu/web/guest/regulations/reach/understanding-reach

Indicates if the substance is listed on the California's OEHHA's Proposition 65 List (https://oehha.ca.gov/proposition-65/proposition-65-list/ ) Proposition 65. Status April 2020. This piece of legislation,  officially known as the Safe Drinking Water and Toxic Enforcement Act of 1986,  was enacted as a ballot initiative in November 1986. The proposition protects the state's drinking water sources from being contaminated with chemicals known to cause cancer,  birth defects or other reproductive harm,  and requires businesses to inform Californians about exposures to such chemicals. Proposition 65 requires the state to maintain and update a list of chemicals known to the state to cause cancer or reproductive toxicity.

Indicates if the substance is listed on the European Chemicals Agency's (ECHA) list of substance evaluation within CoRAP, downloaded on May 1, 2020, from http://echa.europa.eu/web/guest/information-on-chemicals/evaluation/community-rolling-action-plan/corap-table/ . The downloaded version was last updated on April 30, 2020, and contained "382 unique substances/entries." The ECHA explains that "if a substance is on this list, it meanst hat a Member State has evaluated or will evaluate it over the coming years. The lsit is called the Community rolling action plan (CoRAP)." The entry also shows the Status of the assessment, Initial grounds for concern because of which the assessment was initiated, The year when the assessment has started or is to be strated, and evaluating authority (Member State).

StringWithMarkup.String: On EU REACH Restriction List, Annex XVII

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the Restriction list (Annex XVII) within REACH regulation (https://echa.europa.eu/substances-restricted-under-reach/ ). Status April 2020. The entry also gives the Restriction list entry number as given by the ECHA for further reference. See also https://www.echa.europa.eu/web/guest/regulations/reach/understanding-reach/

Indicates if the substance is listed on the U.S. EPA's TSCA (Toxic Substances Control Act) Inventory List and also records its status, as given in the TSCA list. The TSCA inventory contains all existing chemical substances manufactured, processed, or imported in the United States that do not qualify for an exemption or exclusion under TSCA). Downloaded from https://www.epa.gov/tsca-inventory/ in May 2019.

Indicates which substances are classified as endocrine disruptors within EU REACH (i.e., having endocrine disruption hazards listed as the reason for placement on the Candidate list of substances of very high concern (SVHC) for Authorization), status December 2019.

Indicates if the substance is a potential CMR substance (i.e., carcinogenic, mutagenic, or toxic to reproduction) based on the Danish EPA's predicted GHS-aligned hazard classifications. The entry also indicates which CMR classifications have been assigned by the Danish EPA (i.e., Carcinogencity 2 (Carc.2), Mutagenicity 2 (Muta.2), or Toxic to reproduction (Repr.2)).

StringWithMarkup.String: Included on ECHA's Endocrine Disruptor Assessment List

nodes.description: Indicates if the substance is listed on the European Chemicals Agency's (ECHA) "Endocrine disruptor assessment list," downloaded on 30.04.2020 from http://echa.europa.eu/ed-assessment/ . StringWithMarkup.String: On EPA's Safer Chemical Ingredients List

This list is designed to hlp manufacturers find safer chemical alternatives that meet the criteria of the Safer Choice Program." Status April 2020.

StringWithMarkup.String: On the REACH Chemical Universe Mapping List

The entry also shows the tonnage, registration status, and position in the chemical universe, as provided by the ECHA's list.

StringWithMarkup.String: Numbered Source Lists of Food Contact Chemicals included in FCCdb

nodes.description: The columns labeled from S01 through to S67 indicate the appearance of a given substance on the respective information source (e.g., a piece of legislation or an industry inventory etc.). Further details on the information sources used are given in each subcategory (note fc = food contact, FCM = food contact material, consistent with original publication). The presented database aims to include as much information as possible but still does not pretend to be comprehensive. Note that only the openly accessible and easily interrogatable sources were included, and only substances with unique CAS numbers indicated by the source could be included at this stage. To enable comparative analysis or in lieu of other sources for the respective FCM type, the FCCdb also includes several sources in draft form (i.e. not yet in force) or those not in force anymore or soon to be replaced by superceding regulations. Further specific details are provided in the description of each individual source/list (S01-S67).

Downloaded from https://www.iopp.org/files/Food%20Packaging%20Product%20Stewardship%20Considerations%20FSAP-IoPP%20v1_0.pdf. The document provides "a guideline to suppliers of food packaging." It is a "voluntary set of considerations that a supplier or food producer is welcome to use (in whole  or part) as a roadmap for awareness on quality issues and minimizing or eliminating chemicals of concern from food packaging."

CoE List for coatings in food contact. Taken from the Policy statement concerning Coatings intended to come into contact with foodstuffs, Version 3 - 12.02.2009, prepared by Consumer Health Protection Committee, Committee of Experts on Materials Coming into Contact with Food, of Council of Europe (CoE). This list (including lists A, B, C, D) appears identical to the CEPE lists given in several Annexes of Code of practice for coated articles where the food contact layer is a coating, Working Document, Edition 4, 2 February 2009, prepared by CEPE (The voice of paint, printing ink and artists' colours in Europe) (except for Annex XI dual use substances).

EuPIA Inventory List 2013 for printing inks for non-food contact surface of food contact articles. Extracted from the "Inventory list - Version December 2013, Comprising packaging ink raw materials applied to the non-food contact surface of food packaging," by EuPIA (European Printing Ink Association), a sector of CEPE aisbl (see https://www.eupia.org/key-topics/food-contact-materials/raw-material-selection).  Second document linked to from this document, covering photoinitiators, is not included as a separate source (versions 2013, 2018 and 2019, FCCdb sources 31-33, respectively). EuPIA gives following notice: "In 2007, EuPIA decided to collate and make publicly available a list of all the substances used in the manufacture of food packaging inks, with the aim of implementing a transparent tool for packaging converters and brand owners. From 2007 to 2013 the list served with useful function, intending to be a reference for competent authorities and other stakeholders. Since 2010, the amendment on food packaging inks of the Swiss Consumer Goods Ordinance is in force which contains a positive list of substances which only may be used in the manufacture of food packaging inks marketed in Switzerland. Germany follows suit and is discussing a similar approach. The consequence of having such listing in national legislation means the EuPIA Inventory List had become superseded by the evolution of legislation and was no longer relevant as an independent, updated document. As a result, it was decided at the end of 2013 that the EuPIA Inventory List should be closed as a document, but would be maintained for the purposes of historical reference only."

The FCCdb file contains these columns, which refer to sum hazard scores given as part of hazardous substances prioritization study based on data from ECHA C&L or J-GHS sources. Scoring to obtain sum hazard scores was performed separately for health hazards (HH) and environmental hazards (ENVH), separately for the two sources ECHA C&L Inventory and J-GHS. Prioritized list includes substances receiving sum scores >=10000 for HH (as this corresponds to CMR - carcinogenic, mutagenic or toxic for reproduction - substances), and/or >=1000 for ENVH, in at least one of the GHS classifications sources (J-GHS or ECHA C&L Inventory). However, note that outcomes of prioritization case studies would depend on the choice of prioritization criteria, which may differ depending on the study goals.
